\v 33 Don't be fooled: ‘Evil conversations¦119827 corrupt¦119824 good¦119826 character¦119825.’
\v 34 Sober¦119829 up as you should, and stop sinning¦119833, because¦119835 some of you are \add quite\add* ignorant¦119834 about \nd God¦119836\nd*. (I say that to your shame¦119840.)
\s1 Our new immortal bodies
\rem /s1 The Resurrection Body
\p
\v 35 But¦119852 someone¦119846 will ask, “How do the dead¦119850 come back to life and¦119852 what kind of body¦119853 will they¦119854 \add have then¦119852\add*?”
\v 36 Silly question! \add Plants\add* don't¦119859 come to life¦119860 unless the seed dies \add first\add*.
\v 37 And you don't¦119870 sow the plants, but¦119867 you sow the bare seeds—perhaps of wheat¦119882 or something¦119885 else—
\v 38 then \nd God¦119890\nd* gives it a body just like he wants, so each seed gets its own \add new\add* body.
\p
\v 39 Not all bodies are the same¦119908: humans¦119914 have one kind of body¦119906, animals¦119918 have different ones, birds¦119922 different again, and fish also different.
\p
\v 40 There are also heavenly bodies and earthly bodies, but¦119934 the beauty of heavenly bodies and of earthly \add bodies\add* are \add quite\add* different.
\v 41 The sun, the moon¦119953, and the stars all have their own different types of beauty, and even the beauty of stars differs from one to another.
\p
\v 42 So too it¦119973 is with the resurrection¦119967 of the dead¦119969. The decaying body is ‘sown’ \add into the ground\add*, but the raised¦119973 \add body\add* is immortal.
\v 43 It's ‘sown’ in dishonour¦119978 but it's raised in splendour. It's ‘sown’ in weakness¦119984 but it's raised in power¦119987.
\v 44 It's ‘sown’ a natural body but it's raised¦119991 as a spiritual body. (If there's a natural body, there's also a spiritual body.)
\v 45 As it's also written¦120006:\x + \xo 15:45: \xt Gen 2:7.\x* ‘The first¦120009 Adam became a living¦120014 being.’ The last ‘Adam’ is a life-giving spirit¦120019,
\v 46 but¦120026 the spiritual doesn't come first—it's first the natural¦120028 and \em then\em* the spiritual.
\v 47 The first¦120033 man was made of dust from the earth¦120037—the second¦120040 man \add came\add* from heaven¦120046.
\v 48 Earthly people are like \add that\add* earthly man, and¦120055 heavenly people are like \add that\add* heavenly man.
\p
\v 49 And just like we carry the image of \add that\add* earthly¦120071 man, we should also bear the image of \add that\add* heavenly¦120080 man.
\v 50 Now brothers¦120084 and sisters¦120084, I can tell you all that our \add present physical bodies\add* can't¦120092 inherit God's kingdom¦120089, and nor can corrupt¦120097 \add things\add* inherit immortality.
\p
\v 51 Listen¦120102, I'm explaining a mystery¦120103 to you¦120104 all. Not all of us will pass away, but we will all be changed¦120116\x + \xo 15:51-52: \xt 1Th 4:15-17.\x*
\v 52 in an instant¦120118, a \add millisecond\add*, at the last trumpet because¦120130 the trumpet will sound and the dead¦120133 will come back to living as immortals, and we'll be changed¦120139.
\v 53 \add Yes,\add* it's essential for this perishable¦120143 \add body\add* to become incorruptible and¦120147 for this mortal¦120149 to become immortal¦120152.
\v 54 But¦120160 when this perishable¦120156 \add body\add* becomes incorruptible and¦120160 this mortal¦120162 becomes immortal¦120166, then what was written¦120179 will come true:\x + \xo 15:54: \xt Isa 25:8.\x* ‘Death is replaced by victory¦120184.’
\q1
\v 55 \x + \xo 15:55: \xt Hos 13:14 (LXX).\x*‘Death, where is your victory¦120189?
\q1 \add Yes\add* death, where is your sting¦120194?’
\m
